\par \plain\f4\fs28\b Why regions?\plain\f4\fs20 
\par 
\par Region is a Win API word. In Windows, a region is a rectangle, polygon, or ellipse (or a combination of two or more of these shapes) that can be filled, painted, inverted, framed, and used to perform hit testing (testing for the cursor location). 
\par 
\par 
\par \plain\f4\fs28\b Overview
\par \plain\f4\fs20\b 
\par \plain\f4\fs20 Region is a descriptor of non-rectangular or recangular area. The {\uldb krpRegion library}{\v Overview>Main} uses regions for sahapes of controls (the {\uldb TkrpControlRegion}{\v TkrpControlRegion} component) and forms (any of {\uldb Skingines}{\v Skingines>Main} components). Also regions are used as hot area shapes. Regions can be defined as a rectangle or as a set of rectangles. Region can be of any shape, even a grid of pixel by pixel.
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs20 \{bmc Region.bmp\}
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs20 Regoin's bounds rect is called a region box, and can be read by \plain\f4\fs20\b GetRgnBox \plain\f4\fs20 Win API function. To move a Region use the \plain\f4\fs20\b OffsetRgn\plain\f4\fs20  function. Region can be easily inverted (swap visible and invisible pixels) by \plain\f4\fs20\b InvertRgn\plain\f4\fs20  function.
\par 
\par 
\par \plain\f4\fs28\b Regions as Hot Areas
\par \plain\f4\fs20 
\par Hot areas of \plain\f3\fs20 {\uldb skingines}{\v Skingines>Main} use regions as a shape and position identefiers. So the hot area is a region with mouse and drawing support. The hot area supports run-time states, \plain\lang1049\f6\fs20 4\plain\f3\fs20  different run-time are used in the \plain\f4\fs20 {\uldb krpRegion library}{\v Overview>Main}: \plain\lang1049\f6\fs20  \plain\f3\fs20 
\par \plain\f4\fs20 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs20 \{bmc RunTimeStates.bmp\}
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs20 1. \plain\f4\fs20\b Normal\plain\f4\fs20  - default state when the area is not disabled.
\par 2. \plain\f4\fs20\b Selected\plain\f4\fs20  - state when cursor run ower the area and the area is not disabled (Hot track).
\par 3. \plain\f4\fs20\b Active \plain\f4\fs20 - state when mouse clicked and the area responds this click as activate event (Pressed).
\par 4. \plain\f4\fs20\b Disabled\plain\f4\fs20  - state when the area doesn't respond any of mouse or other events. 
\par 
\par \plain\f3\fs20 {\uldb Skingine}{\v Skingines>Main} draws each region depending on it's current run-time state. If region is \plain\f4\fs20\b Normal\plain\f4\fs20 , the normal state picture is used for drawing. \plain\f3\fs20 If region is \plain\f4\fs20\b Selected\plain\f4\fs20 , the selected state picture is used, and so on. You can define which of runtime states are supported by each of hot areas (see \plain\f4\fs20\b RunTimeStates\plain\f4\fs20  property), this feature helps create static regions and, for example, skip \plain\f4\fs20\b Selected\plain\f4\fs20  (Hot track) state. 
\par 
