\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20     Our skin format was designed after analyzing of tons other skin formats. We hope this format will be useful and popular. Remember our skin format is \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\cf4\b open\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  and \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\cf4\b free\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b !\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  Any new ideas and propositions are \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\cf4\b welcome\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b !\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  Send you propositions to: {\uldb karpolan@ABFsoftware.com}{\v !ExecFile("mailto:karpolan@ABFsoftware.com?subject=Skin format")}
\par 
\par We decide to use \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b 4 run-time states\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  for all active areas of program's user interface: 
\par \pard\li720\fi-360\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Normal\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  - default state when the area is not disabled. 
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Selected\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  - state when cursor run ower the area and area is not disabled (Hot track). 
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Active\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 - state when mouse is clicked and area responds this click as activating event (Pressed). 
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Disabled\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  - state when the area doesn't respond any events. 
\par 
\par \pard\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 The skin should conatins images for all \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b run-time states\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  used in your program. Active areas of program painted depending on its \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b run-time state\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 , so when you run mouse over some area it will be viewed as \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Selected\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 , press some area and it will be viewed as \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Active\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  and so on... These are examples of skin images (\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Normal\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 , \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Selected\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  and \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Active\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 ):
\par 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f3\fs20 \{bmc skin_Normal.bmp\} \{bmc skin_Selected.bmp\} \{bmc skin_Active.bmp\}\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 
\par \pard\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 
\par \tab 
\par As you see only active areas should be painted at all images, static areas are viewed as it are on \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Normal\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  image. This feature helps decrerase the size of skin files.
\par 
\par Also our skin format supports \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b masks\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 . \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Masks\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  can be used to define a shape of the application window or as an area descriptor of the user interface, as it used in {\uldb AREA_BY_COLOR}{\v AREA_BY_COLOR>Main} algorithm. \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Mask\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  can be a \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b mono\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  or \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b multi-color\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 ... These are examples of skin masks (\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b mono\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  and \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b multi-color\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 ):
\par \pard\qc\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 
\par \plain\f3\fs20 \{bmc mask_Mono.bmp\} \{bmc mask_Color.bmp\}
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 
\par \pard\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20 We've designed a \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b skin description file format\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  too. This format can be changed in future but we will support all versions of it. \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Skin description file\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  is a standars windows *.INI file with following section and variables:
\par 
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b [Pictures]\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  - this section contains names of all \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b skin image\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  files. File names can be relative (Mask = ..\\A\\Mask.gif).
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Mask\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = file name of \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b mask\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  graphic.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Normal\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = file name of \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b normal\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  image.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Selected\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = file name of \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b selected\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  image.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Active\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = file name of \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b active\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  image.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Disabled\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = file name of \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b disabled\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  image.
\par 
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b [FileInfo]\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  - this section contains inforamtion about skin file.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Project\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = specifies the project skin was designed for... We advice to use application \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b exe name\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  (\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Lens.exe\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  for example) for that.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Description\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = description of the skin (Name, signature e.t.c).
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Version\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = version of the skin.
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Author\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = author information (Name, nickname e.t.c).
\par \plain\lang1058\f3\fs20\b Copyright\plain\lang1058\f3\fs20  = legal copyright inforamtion.
\par 
